== Coal == [[Sines Municipality|Sines]] power plant (hard coal) started operation in 1985-1989 in Portugal. According to WWF its {{CO2}} emissions were among the top dirty ones in Portugal in 2007.<ref>Dirty Thirty WWF 2007</ref>
== Natural gas == [[Maghreb–Europe Gas Pipeline]] (MEG) is a [[natural gas]] pipeline, from [[Algeria]] through [[Morocco]] to [[Andalusia]], [[Spain]],
==Renewable energy== {{Main|Renewable energy in Portugal}} [[EU directive]] has a binding 31% target of renewables up from 20.5% in 2005. According to the Portuguese National Renewable Energy Action Plan by 2020 electricity will be produced: [[wind power]] 23% 14.6 TWh, of which 99% onshore, [[hydro power]] 22% 14.1 TWh, [[biomass]] 5% 3.52 TWh and [[photovoltaic]] solar power 2% 1.5 TWh and [[concentrated solar power]] 2% 1 TWh.<ref>[http://www.ewea.org/fileadmin/ewea_documents/documents/publications/reports/EWEA_EU_Energy_Policy_to_2050.pdf EU Energy Policy to 2050] Achieving 80-95% emissions reductions, [[EWEA]] March 2011</ref>
=== Solar === Portugal has surported and increased the solar electricity ([[Photovoltaic]] power) and solar thermal energy ([[solar heating]]) during 2006-2010. Portugal was 9th in [[Solar power in the European Union|solar heating in the EU]] and 8th in solar power based on total volume in 2010.
==Nuclear power== {{Main|Nuclear energy in Portugal}} There were no nuclear power plants in Portugal as of 2017.
==Electricity in Portugal== [[File:Candeeiros junto à Igreja de Santa Leocádia de Briteiros 01.jpg|alt=|thumb|A Portuguese street lamp]] {{Main|Electricity sector in Portugal}}
Electricity use (gross production + imports – exports – losses) was 51.2 TWh in 2008. Portugal imported 9 TWh electricity in 2008. Population was 10.6 million.<ref>IEA Key energy statistics 2010 Page: 27, 54</ref> In 2014 electricity was generated by 30% hydroelectricity, 27% natural gas, 22% wind, 20% coal and 1% solar.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bp.com/content/dam/bp/excel/energy-economics/statistical-review-2015/bp-statistical-review-of-world-energy-2015-workbook.xlsx |format=XLSX |title=BP Statistical Review of World Energy June 2015 |website=Bp.com |accessdate=2016-11-06 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620001414/http://www.bp.com/content/dam/bp/excel/Energy-Economics/statistical-review-2015/bp-statistical-review-of-world-energy-2015-workbook.xlsx |archivedate=2015-06-20 |df= }}</ref>
== Transport == The sustainable strategy has been a shift from individual to collective transport within the Lisbon Metropolitan Area ([[Lisbon Metro|Metro Lisbon]] (ML), collective buses, [[Carris|Companhia Carris de ferro de Lisboa]]).
==Global warming== {{Main|Climate change in Portugal}} {| class="wikitable" ! colspan="3" style="text-align:center; background:#cfb;"| CO<sub>2</sub> emissions in 2009 (million tonnes)<ref name=IEApop2011>{{cite web|url=http://www.iea.org/co2highlights/co2Highlights.XLS|format=XLS|title=CO2 Emissions from Fuel Combustion|website=Iea.org|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=IEA Key World Energy Statistics|url=http://www.iea.org/textbase/nppdf/free/2011/key_world_energy_stats.pdf|format=PDF|quotation=2011, October, population in the end tables|website=Iea.org|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref> |- ! style="background:#cfb;"| ! style="background:#cfb;"| {{CO2}} ! style="background:#cfb;"| People (million) |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Chile|Chile]] || style="text-align:right;"| 66 || style="text-align:right;"| 16.8 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Belarus|Belarus]] || style="text-align:right;"| 61 || style="text-align:right;"| 9.7 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Syria|Syria]] || style="text-align:right;"| 57 || style="text-align:right;"| 21.2 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Turkmenistan|Turkmenistan]] || style="text-align:right;"| 57 || style="text-align:right;"| 5.0 |- | style="text-align:left;"| Portugal || style="text-align:right;"| 57 || style="text-align:right;"| 10.6 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]] || style="text-align:right;"| 55 || style="text-align:right;"| 160.0 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Libya|Libya]] || style="text-align:right;"| 55 || style="text-align:right;"| 6.3 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Serbia|Serbia]] || style="text-align:right;"| 52 || style="text-align:right;"| 7.4 |- | style="text-align:left;"| [[Energy in Finland|Finland]] || style="text-align:right;"| 52 || style="text-align:right;"| 5.3 |} According to [[Energy Information Administration]] the {{CO2}} emissions from energy consumption of Portugal were in 2009 56.5 Mt, slightly over [[Energy in Bangladesh|Bangladesh]] with 160 million people and [[Energy in Finland|Finland]] with 5.3 million people.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2011/jan/31/world-carbon-dioxide-emissions-country-data-co2 |title= World carbon dioxide emissions data by country: China speeds ahead of the rest|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=31 January 2011|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref> The emissions per capita were (tonnes): Portugal 5.58, [[Energy in India|India]] 1.38, [[Energy in China|China]] 5.83, [[Energy in Europe|Europe]] 7.14, [[Energy in Russia|Russia]] 11.23, [[Energy in the North America|North America]] 14.19, [[Energy in Singapore|Singapore]] 34.59 and [[Energy in the United Arab Emirates|United Arab Emirates]] 40.31.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/datablog/2011/jan/31/world-carbon-dioxide-emissions-country-data-co2 |title=World carbon dioxide emissions country data co2|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2016-11-06}}</ref>
