'''Magnadur''' is a [[sintering|sintered]] [[barium]] [[allotropes of iron|ferrite]], specifically BaFe<sub>12</sub>O<sub>19</sub> in an [[anisotropic]] form.<ref>{{cite book|page=132|ISBN=0-582-35448-X|title=Book of Data}}</ref> It is used for making [[permanent magnet]]s. The material was invented by [[Mullard]] and was used initially particularly for focussing rings on [[cathode ray tubes]]. Magnadur magnets retain their magnetism well, and are often used in education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://practicalphysics.org/play-magnets.html|title=Play with magnets|website=practicalphysics.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=Understanding Primary Science: Ideas, Concepts and Explanations|first=Martin W.|last=Wenham|date=18 November 2004|publisher=SAGE Publications Ltd|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/Understanding-Primary-Science-Concepts-Explanations/dp/1412901634/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1523277554&sr=1-1&keywords=9781412901635|isbn=1412901634|p=234}}</ref> Magnadur can also be used in [[DC motor]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Magnadur Magnets for Direct Current Motors|date=31 December 1970|publisher=Mullard Ltd|ISBN=0901232106}}</ref>

==Physical characteristics==
* [[Remanence]] 0.9 T
* [[Coercivity]] 110 kA/m
* Maximum [[energy product]], 20 kJm{{Sup|-3}} - at 86 kSm{{sup|-1}}

