{{Other uses|TOW (disambiguation)}}
[[File:Drev och drevjärn samt träklubba 004.jpg|thumb|[[Caulking]] tools with tow]]

In the [[textile industry]], a '''tow''' is a coarse, broken fibre, removed during processing [[flax]], [[hemp]], or [[jute]].<ref>{{cite web|  |title=Tow|website=Glossary of Colonial Terms|publisher= History Online| |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915135150/http://www.chaddsfordhistory.org/history/glossary.htm |date=September 15, 2007 }}</ref> Flax tows are often used as [[upholstery]] stuffing, and tows in general are frequently cut up to produce [[staple fibre]].  The very light color of flax tow is the source of the word "[[wikt:towhead|towhead]]", meaning a person with naturally tousled light blonde hair.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://etymonline.com/index.php?allowed_in_frame=0&search=towhead |title=Towhead| website= Online Etymology Dictionary|access-date= November 28, 2016}}</ref>

In the [[artificial fibre]] and [[Composite material|composites]] industries, a '''tow''' is an untwisted [[wikt:bundle|bundle]] of continuous [[Filament (textiles)|filaments]], in particular of [[acrylic fibre|acrylic]],  [[carbon fibres]], or [[viscose rayon]]. Tows are designated either by their total [[Tex (unit)|tex]] (mass per unit length) or by the number of fibres they contain.{{dubious|date=May 2017|reason=Not in my experience they aren't, and I used to work in that industry. For me, 12K = 12ktex}} For example, a 12K tow contains about 12,000 fibres.{{citation needed|date = November 2016}}

